<!-- ===== BLOG ===== -->
<section id="blog" style="padding-top:80px;">
  <div class="sh">
    <div class="si-idx">06</div>
    <div>
      <div class="s-tag">Technical Writing</div>
      <h2 class="s-title">Operator Knowledge,<br>Made Transferable</h2>
      <p class="s-desc">Written from production incidents and architectural decisions, grounded in careful documentation review and industry-proven architectural patterns.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="blog-list">
    <% blogPosts.forEach(function(post, index) { %>
    <button type="button" class="blog-item" data-blog-index="<%= index %>">
      <div class="b-meta"><span class="b-n"><%= post.id %></span><span class="b-cat"><%= post.category %></span></div>
      <div class="b-title"><%= post.title %></div>
      <div class="b-arr">→</div>
    </button>
    <div class="blog-content" data-blog-content="<%= index %>">
      <div class="blog-content-inner">
        <% if (post.id === '001') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">High-volume referer spam campaigns observed in production environments can overwhelm origin infrastructure while evading simple rate limits through adaptive patterns and rotating user agents.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Blocking legitimate crawlers damages SEO. Overly aggressive rules create false positives. Static rules are bypassed quickly by adaptive attacks. Origin infrastructure degrades under sustained load.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Layered defenses reduce single points of failure. Edge WAF expression rules handle pattern signatures before origin processing. IP-level rate limiting with burst allowances preserves legitimate traffic. Bot verification for unverified traffic adds another layer. Origin-level CRS with path-scoped exclusions provides defense-in-depth.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Edge rules reduce origin load but require edge platform capabilities. Bot verification introduces latency for unverified traffic. CRS tuning requires audit-mode validation to prevent false positives. Multiple layers increase operational complexity but improve resilience.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Deploy edge rules first to reduce origin load. Enable origin CRS in detection-only mode, analyze audit logs to identify false positives, apply path-scoped exclusions, then enable enforcement. Progressive rollback of emergency rules as traffic normalizes. Rules derived from observed traffic patterns, not generic templates.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '002') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">OWASP CRS at higher paranoia levels, when applied in production environments, can block legitimate application traffic due to structural similarities between valid parameters and attack signatures.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Blanket paranoia reduction reduces protection coverage. Global rule disables create security gaps. Production environments cannot tolerate widespread false positives that break legitimate functionality.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Path-scoped exclusions preserve protection coverage while eliminating false positives. Detection-only mode enables validation before enforcement. Rule-level granularity allows surgical adjustments without reducing overall security posture.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Path-scoped exclusions require maintenance and version control. Detection-only mode delays protection but enables validation. Rule-level tuning increases operational complexity but improves precision.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Switch to detection-only mode on affected vhosts. Query audit logs to identify specific rule IDs and request paths. Apply path-scoped exclusions using SecRuleRemoveById and SecRuleUpdateTargetById. Validate against captured production request samples before re-enabling enforcement. Exclusion logic version-controlled and applied consistently.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '003') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">High container density on single hosts, observed in production environments, can lead to resource contention and cascading failures when all containers use identical resource templates regardless of traffic patterns.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Flat resource allocation wastes capacity on idle containers while starving active ones. Container restarts cause full-fleet outages. Resource contention triggers cascading failures. Staging environments rarely match production density for testing.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Resource tiering based on actual usage patterns increases effective capacity. Traffic-based classification enables right-sizing. On-demand process managers for idle containers reclaim resources. Rolling batch changes prevent full-fleet restarts.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Tiered configurations increase operational complexity. Classification requires monitoring and analysis. On-demand managers add latency for cold starts. Rolling changes take longer but reduce risk.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Analyze request volume per container, classify into tiers (high/medium/low/idle), generate tiered configuration templates, deploy via automation with reload capabilities, move idle containers to ondemand mode, monitor for saturation reduction. Changes reversible and applied incrementally.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '004') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Backup automation pipelines observed in production can silently fail when scripts exit successfully but produce invalid output, creating gaps that are only discovered during restore attempts.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Exit code zero does not guarantee valid output. Silent failures compound over time. Restore failures discovered too late result in data loss. Trust-based workflows fail without validation.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Assertion-based validation catches failures immediately. Independent verification paths ensure separation of failure modes from primary processes. Output validation before retention prevents invalid data from being stored. Multiple validation checkpoints reduce single points of failure.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Validation adds latency and complexity. Independent verification requires additional infrastructure. Multiple checkpoints increase operational overhead but improve reliability.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Post-dump validation checks file size and basic integrity. Transfer operations validate source path and file size before sync. Independent audit jobs verify stored artifacts out-of-band. Any validation failure triggers non-zero exit and alert. Assertion-based validation rather than trust-based workflows.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '005') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Legacy Ingress controllers face deprecation risks in Kubernetes environments. Routing semantics can change between versions, creating inconsistencies that silently misroute traffic.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Maintenance windows are not always available. Routing changes can affect multiple namespaces. TLS provisioning must remain functional throughout migration. Big-bang migrations risk service disruption.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Staged migrations with per-namespace reversibility enable zero-downtime transitions. HTTPRoute provides clearer routing semantics and long-term stability on maintained specifications. Dual controllers maintain service availability during migration.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Staged migrations take longer but reduce risk. Dual controllers increase resource usage temporarily. Route-by-route migration requires careful coordination but enables rollback per namespace.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Deploy Gateway API controller with separate GatewayClass (no traffic impact). Convert Ingress to HTTPRoute namespace-by-namespace. Use kubectl diff and --dry-run=server for validation. Update cert-manager to use new IngressClass annotation. DNS cutover per service with fast rollback capability. Maintain dual controllers until migration is stable.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '006') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Default monitoring dashboards in high-density container environments often miss critical metrics where per-container granularity is essential but aggregation can hide issues.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Container-level failures can cascade before host-level metrics show problems. Default dashboards aggregate too much. Log correlation across hosts requires proper tooling. Relying solely on host-level metrics misses container-specific issues.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Per-container visibility is essential at high density. Custom dashboards tailored to environment-specific patterns surface issues that default views miss. Log correlation enables root cause analysis across distributed systems. Metrics and logs must be correlated via shared labels.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Per-container metrics increase storage and query load. Custom dashboards require maintenance. Log aggregation adds infrastructure complexity but improves observability.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Deploy cAdvisor for per-container metrics. Use Node Exporter for host-level context. Configure Prometheus to scrape both. Build custom Grafana dashboards for container-dense environments with alerts on saturation thresholds. Set up Loki for log aggregation with label-based filtering. Correlate metrics with logs via shared labels.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '007') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Internal platforms that list fifteen tools and zero opinions see slow adoption. Developers route around the catalog and SSH credentials leak back into Slack threads.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Shadow clusters, duplicate CI jobs, and &ldquo;temporary&rdquo; admin roles become permanent. The platform team measures success by CRDs installed instead of deployments shipped.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Pick three blessed flows (for example: stateless API, batch worker, static site) with batteries-included logging, ingress, and secrets. Everything else is an explicit exception with a design note.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Opinionated paths frustrate edge cases until escape hatches are documented. Saying no is part of the product.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Ship a cookiecutter or Backstage template per path, wire default NetworkPolicies and PodSecurity standards, and delete unused tiles from the portal quarterly. If a workflow has no owner on call, it is not golden.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '008') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Teams bolt on Trivy in CI, celebrate zero CRITICAL findings, and still cannot answer who built the artifact running in prod.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Unsigned images, mutable tags, and replayed pipelines erode trust. Admission controllers either block nothing or block everything after one bad Friday deploy.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Ordering matters: generate SBOMs first, attach signatures from CI with OIDC, store attestations beside the digest, then teach Kyverno or Gatekeeper to require digest pulls plus valid signature for the workload identity.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Cold start latency in CI and occasional keyless outage windows. Policy exceptions must be time-bounded and audited.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Block <code>:latest</code> in prod namespaces, require image digest in manifests, and map each running digest to a Git SHA in your deploy system. Run table-top exercises for &ldquo;compromised build account&rdquo; twice a year.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '009') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Long-running automated jobs in public CI can harvest credentials when workflows use tokens with write scope on popular repositories. In early 2026 reporting, abuse targeted high-profile orgs and tooling vendors; in at least one case a container scanner&rsquo;s release path was affected, which is a reminder that &ldquo;trusted&rdquo; binaries start at the pipeline.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">A single leaked <code>GITHUB_TOKEN</code> or publish secret becomes a supply-chain event: malicious releases, poisoned caches, or repo takeover. Forks and workflow triggers widen who can run code next to secrets.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Treat CI like prod: least privilege on tokens, OIDC to cloud and registries, branch protection, required reviews for workflow changes, and pin third-party actions to immutable SHAs. Separate build, sign, and promote steps so one job cannot do everything.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Tighter policies slow contributors and complicate forks. The alternative is incident response at ecosystem scale.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Audit <code>pull_request_target</code> and <code>workflow_run</code> usage, disable unnecessary write permissions, use environments with protection rules for releases, and rotate credentials after any tooling advisory. Verify release artifacts out-of-band (checksums, sigstore) before you roll them to clusters.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '010') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">What it is</div><div class="b-txt"><a href="https://kubernetes.io/blog/2026/03/20/ingress2gateway-1-0-release/" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ingress2Gateway 1.0</a> is a migration assistant from SIG Network. It reads your existing <code>Ingress</code> manifests (including many Ingress-NGINX annotations) and prints Gateway API resources (<code>Gateway</code>, <code>HTTPRoute</code>, and related objects) so you can modernize routing without guessing every edge case by hand.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Why it matters now</div><div class="b-txt">Ingress-NGINX is on a retirement timeline; Gateway API is where vendors and the project are investing. The hard part is not YAML syntax, it is behavior: redirects, regex paths, timeouts, CORS, and snippets that never mapped 1:1 to portable APIs.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">What 1.0 adds</div><div class="b-txt">Broader Ingress-NGINX annotation coverage (on the order of dozens of common keys), controller-level integration tests that compare live behavior between Ingress-NGINX and Gateway implementations, and clearer warnings when something cannot translate cleanly (so you fix it before cutover, not after).</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">How to use it safely</div><div class="b-txt">Run the tool against files or live cluster state, review generated manifests and every WARN line, apply to a non-prod cluster, and validate traffic (including TLS and redirects) against your current controller. Keep Ingress and Gateway dual-running per namespace until metrics and error rates look boring.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Reality check</div><div class="b-txt">It is an assistant, not a magic button. Some annotations (for example fragile snippets) will stay manual work. That is still cheaper than rediscovering those behaviors in production.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '011') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Finance and engineering often talk past each other: Kubernetes shows requests and limits; the cloud bill shows instances, disks, egress, and support SKUs. Without a reconciliation story, FinOps becomes a monthly argument instead of a feedback loop.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Teams right-size pods on paper while idle nodes stay warm for DaemonSets and system pods. Shared clusters hide noisy-neighbor cost. Showback dashboards that ignore discounts, savings plans, or committed use look authoritative and are wrong.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Treat allocation as a data integration problem: ingest cloud CUR (or equivalent), map usage types to namespaces and teams with consistent labels, and expose both &ldquo;Kubernetes-allocatable&rdquo; and &ldquo;invoice-adjacent&rdquo; views. The <a href="https://www.finops.org/framework/" rel="noopener noreferrer">FinOps Framework</a> phases (Inform, Optimize, Operate) map cleanly to iterative label discipline and tier-1 review cadences.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Full allocation accuracy is expensive. Chargeback can slow innovation if every experiment needs a cost center. Start with showback, shared overhead buckets, and documented assumptions.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Require <code>team</code> and <code>cost-center</code> labels on namespaces and workloads; reconcile node pool SKUs against pod requests weekly; use OpenCost-class tooling for directional signal, then tighten with billing exports. Tie savings work to SLO owners, not only central FinOps.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '012') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">CPU and memory averages hide work that is bursty or queue-driven. Message consumers, batch workers, and gRPC services often need scaling signals tied to lag, saturation, or error budget burn, not smoothed utilization.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">HPA thrashes when metrics have the wrong window. Scaling on unsmoothed queue depth without max replicas caps causes stampedes. Custom metrics without SLO guardrails scale into debt (more replicas, same error rate).</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">The upstream <a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/run-application/horizontal-pod-autoscale/" rel="noopener noreferrer">Horizontal Pod Autoscaler</a> supports custom and external metrics via the metrics API; <a href="https://keda.sh/docs/" rel="noopener noreferrer">KEDA</a> turns event sources and scalers into first-class scale objects. Pick the smallest abstraction that matches your signal (Prometheus adapter vs KEDA ScaledObject) and document ownership.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">More scalers mean more failure modes in the control plane. Event-driven scaling needs idempotent consumers and safe max replicas. Testing requires load that matches production skew, not synthetic ramps.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Define SLO and a primary scaling signal (for example Kafka consumer lag or Redis list length). Add stabilization windows, min/max replicas, and alerts on &ldquo;at max for N minutes.&rdquo; Game-day scale-down to verify backlog recovery. Keep HPA/KEDA manifests in GitOps next to the Deployment.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '013') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Operators bundle operational knowledge, but they also ship CRDs that evolve. Kubernetes relies on stored versions, conversion webhooks, and careful upgrade ordering; skipping that model is how you strand clients on deprecated shapes.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Applying a new operator manifest upgrades CRDs cluster-wide: a bad webhook or defaulting change breaks every namespace. Helm hooks that mutate CRDs out of band desync from GitOps. Clients caching old OpenAPI schemas send invalid objects silently.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Follow the <a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/extend-kubernetes/custom-resources/custom-resource-definition-versioning/" rel="noopener noreferrer">CRD versioning</a> guidance: multiple served versions, a single storage version, and conversion when needed. Treat operator upgrades like data migrations: backup etcd snapshots where policy allows, rehearse on a shadow cluster, and pin versions per environment.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Conversion webhooks add latency and availability coupling. Delaying upgrades accumulates CVE and compatibility debt. Too many served versions increases client confusion.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Read upstream release notes for CRD schema changes; run <code>kubectl diff</code> against live CRDs; validate with representative custom resources in CI; roll canary namespaces before fleet-wide promotion. Keep a rollback path (previous operator bundle + known-good CRD set).</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '014') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">OpenTelemetry gives a unified pipeline, but raw span volume can dwarf useful signal. High-cardinality labels (unbounded user IDs, raw URLs) explode backend cost and slow queries. Teams need explicit budgets and sampling policies, not &ldquo;collect everything and filter later.&rdquo;</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">Tail sampling misconfigured drops error spans. Head sampling hides rare failures. Dashboards built on unsampled metrics disagree with traces during incidents.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Align with <a href="https://opentelemetry.io/docs/concepts/sampling/" rel="noopener noreferrer">OpenTelemetry sampling</a> models: probabilistic head sampling for volume control, tail sampling in the collector for error retention, and consistent attributes across metrics, logs, and traces. Pair with RED/USE-style golden signals at low cardinality.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Tail sampling needs buffering and adds latency. Aggressive cardinality limits frustrate debugging until you document safe high-cardinality escape hatches (temporary feature flags).</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Inventory top metric and span labels monthly; block new labels in CI where possible; keep error and high-latency paths always-on in tail policies; drill incidents using the same views SRE trains on, not ad-hoc full fidelity.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '015') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Model Context Protocol (MCP) and similar tool bridges let assistants call APIs, run queries, and mutate systems. That is powerful for toil reduction and dangerous if credentials or scopes are wide.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Failure mode</div><div class="b-txt">A prompt injection that reaches an MCP server with cluster-admin becomes an incident. Non-repudiation disappears when humans cannot tell whether a change was human, bot, or blended. Shadow automation bypasses change windows and breaks compliance evidence.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Architectural reasoning</div><div class="b-txt">Treat agents like service accounts: scoped RBAC, short-lived tokens, read-only defaults, and separate identities per environment. Log tool calls with correlation IDs tied to tickets. Follow vendor-neutral hygiene from NIST-style AI risk framing and your own change-management policy; the <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io/" rel="noopener noreferrer">MCP specification</a> is transport and capability negotiation, not a security boundary by itself.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Trade-offs</div><div class="b-txt">Tight scopes slow the demo. Human-in-the-loop gates add latency but preserve accountability.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Implementation pattern</div><div class="b-txt">Start with read-only MCP tools (logs, metrics, docs). Add mutation behind approval workflows or deployment pipelines. Rotate credentials on the same schedule as CI tokens. Red-team prompt paths quarterly.</div></div>
        <% } else if (post.id === '016') { %>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Summary</div><div class="b-txt">Clean up the root <code>CLAUDE.md</code> and the copies nested in each project. The point is not to delete rules that change behavior. The point is to strip everything that burns context without adding executable value.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Why it matters</div><div class="b-txt">That file behaves like a standing system prompt. When it is long, repetitive, or full of essays and warnings instead of instructions, every turn pays tokens for noise. Real directives get buried, so the model attends to the wrong lines.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">What breaks</div><div class="b-txt">Higher token use per turn<br>Cost adds up across sessions<br>The context window fills with low-signal text<br>Less room for code, diffs, and logs<br>Harder to see the rules that actually matter</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Intent</div><div class="b-txt">Keep one hundred percent of functional value. Shrink size aggressively. Same behavior, fewer tokens, clearer focus.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Keep</div><div class="b-txt">Technical rules, shell commands, file paths, code samples, required workflows, security constraints, and explicit notes on what to update and when.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Remove or shorten</div><div class="b-txt">Long motivation for why a rule exists, duplicated sections, redundant checklists, pep-talk warnings, and prose that can become one tight bullet or table.</div></div>
        <div class="b-sec"><div class="b-lbl">Prompt</div><div class="b-txt">Use the block below as a single message to an agent. Copy the whole thing, then run it against your tree.</div></div>
        <div class="prompt-sheet" role="region" aria-label="Copy-paste prompt for optimizing CLAUDE.md files">
          <div class="prompt-sheet-bar">
            <span class="prompt-sheet-label">Copy-paste prompt</span>
            <button type="button" class="prompt-sheet-copy" data-copy-target="prompt-claude-md-016" aria-label="Copy prompt to clipboard">Copy</button>
          </div>
          <pre class="prompt-sheet-body" id="prompt-claude-md-016">Optimize all my CLAUDE.md files to minimize token usage without losing any functional power.

Rules:
• Keep ALL technical rules, code patterns, commands, and &quot;what to update when&quot; instructions
• Remove verbose explanations of why rules exist, just keep the rule itself
• Remove repeated &quot;when to use&quot; checklists that restate the obvious
• Remove motivational/warning paragraphs (&quot;do NOT skip this&quot;, &quot;remember: X is important&quot;)
• Condense bullet lists, if 5 bullets say the same thing, make it 1
• Replace long prose with tables or compact bullet points where possible
• Never remove: code examples, file paths, CLI commands, security patterns, mandatory workflows

Process:
Find all CLAUDE.md files across all projects in memory
Read each file fully before optimizing
Write optimized versions, target 40 to 60 percent reduction in line count
Do NOT touch files that are already concise (under ~30 lines)

Goal:
Same behavior, half the tokens per session</pre>
        </div>
        <% } %>
      </div>
    </div>
    <% }); %>
  </div>
</section>
